    <para id="para-00011">Generally accepted as a draw or possibly a narrow Hittite victory, the fighting at Qadesh is most memorable for ultimately leading the two forces to recognize that they had more to gain from peace than war. In 1258 BCE, the Hittite king <term class="no-emphasis" id="term-00016">Hattusilis II</term> and the Egyptian Pharaoh <term class="no-emphasis" id="term-00017">Ramesses II</term> signed one of early history’s greatest peace treaties (<link target-id="fig-00004"/>). The agreement confirmed Hittite control of Syria and Egyptian dominance over the Phoenician ports of the eastern Mediterranean. However, little more than fifty years later, the once-powerful Hittite Empire collapsed, never to reappear.</para>
    <figure class="scaled-down-30" id="fig-00004">
